      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Including explicit lighting terms ("
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "\"same lighting\"",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": ", "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "\"continuous shadow direction\"",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": ") is especially important because lighting is the hardest attribute to maintain across extension steps. The model has no explicit 3D light source model — it relies entirely on the visible edge pixels and the prompt."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "horizontalRule"
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "ControlNet-Guided Outpainting"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "For scenes with strong structural constraints — architecture, grid floors, converging perspective lines — adding a ControlNet condition to the outpainting window significantly improves coherence. The depth or edge ControlNet provides spatial constraints that text alone cannot supply."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "from diffusers import StableDiffusionControlNetInpaintPipeline, ControlNetModel\nfrom transformers import pipeline as hf_pipeline\nimport torch\nimport numpy as np\nfrom PIL import Image\n\n# Load depth estimator for the source image\ndepth_estimator = hf_pipeline(\n    \"depth-estimation\",\n    model=\"Intel/dpt-large\",\n    device=0,\n)\n\ncontrolnet = ControlNetModel.from_pretrained(\n    \"lllyasviel/sd-controlnet-depth\",\n    torch_dtype=torch.float16,\n)\npipe = StableDiffusionControlNetInpaintPipeline.from_pretrained(\n    \"runwayml/stable-diffusion-inpainting\",\n    controlnet=controlnet,\n    torch_dtype=torch.float16,\n).to(\"cuda\")\n\n\ndef outpaint_with_depth(crop: Image.Image, mask: Image.Image, prompt: str) -> Image.Image:\n    # Estimate depth of the current window (including already-generated pixels)\n    depth_result = depth_estimator(crop)\n    depth_np = np.array(depth_result[\"depth\"].convert(\"RGB\"))\n    depth_img = Image.fromarray(depth_np)\n\n    return pipe(\n        prompt=prompt,\n        negative_prompt=\"blurry, distorted, low quality\",\n        image=crop,\n        mask_image=mask,\n        control_image=depth_img,\n        controlnet_conditioning_scale=0.7,  # structural guidance\n        strength=1.0,\n        guidance_scale=8.0,\n        num_inference_steps=40,\n    ).images[0]"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Using the depth map of the current window (not just the original) ensures that depth consistency propagates forward step by step — each new extension inherits the depth structure that the previous step generated."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "horizontalRule"
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Panorama Generation"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Outpainting is a natural fit for panorama generation: extend a scene left and right until the total width is 3–4× the original, producing wide-format hero images, 360° scene starters, or wallpapers."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "from PIL import Image\n\ndef generate_panorama(\n    seed_image: Image.Image,\n    total_width: int,\n    prompt: str,\n    step_size: int = 128,\n) -> Image.Image:\n    W, H = seed_image.size\n    \n    # Anchor seed in the centre of the panorama\n    canvas = Image.new(\"RGB\", (total_width, H), (0, 0, 0))\n    x_start = (total_width - W) // 2\n    canvas.paste(seed_image, (x_start, 0))\n\n    orig_np = np.array(seed_image)\n\n    # Extend right from centre\n    canvas_np = np.array(canvas)\n    canvas_np[:, x_start + W:] = orig_np[:, -1:]  # fill with edge colour\n    # ... run outpaint_right on canvas_np ...\n\n    # Flip and extend left (same function, flipped canvas)\n    canvas_flipped = Image.fromarray(canvas_np).transpose(Image.FLIP_LEFT_RIGHT)\n    # ... run outpaint_right on flipped canvas ...\n    canvas_np = np.array(canvas_flipped.transpose(Image.FLIP_LEFT_RIGHT))\n\n    return Image.fromarray(canvas_np)\n\npanorama = generate_panorama(\n    seed_image=Image.open(\"scene.png\").resize((512, 512)),\n    total_width=2560,\n    prompt=\"sweeping mountain valley, sunrise, photorealistic, 8k, seamless\",\n)"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "horizontalRule"
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Aspect Ratio Conversion"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "A practical and common use case is converting portrait images to landscape format (or vice versa) for different display platforms. Outpainting can add side content to turn a 9:16 portrait into a 16:9 landscape."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "def portrait_to_landscape(\n    portrait: Image.Image,\n    target_ratio: tuple = (16, 9),\n    prompt: str = \"\",\n) -> Image.Image:\n    W, H = portrait.size  # e.g. 576 × 1024\n    target_W = int(H * target_ratio[0] / target_ratio[1])  # 1820 for 16:9\n    pad = (target_W - W) // 2  # equal padding left and right\n\n    # Start with padded canvas, original centred\n    canvas = Image.new(\"RGB\", (target_W, H))\n    canvas.paste(portrait, (pad, 0))\n\n    # Use subject-aware prompt\n    if not prompt:\n        prompt = \"natural background, same lighting and environment as the subject\"\n\n    # Extend left and right simultaneously by iterating from both edges\n    # (or extend right on the flipped image for left side)\n    return outpaint_all_directions(\n        original=portrait,\n        pad_left=pad,\n        pad_right=target_W - W - pad,\n        pad_top=0,\n        pad_bottom=0,\n        prompt=prompt,\n    )"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "horizontalRule"
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Step Size and Window Overlap Trade-offs"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "step_size",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " parameter controls how much new canvas each iteration covers. Smaller steps mean more iterations but better continuity; larger steps are faster but risk visible discontinuities."
          }
        ]
      },
