      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Rule of thumb: keep at least 50% of the window overlapping already-generated content. With a 512×512 window, "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "step_size=128",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " gives 384px of overlap — enough for the model to see existing context while generating only 128 new pixels per step."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "horizontalRule"
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Quality Control and Retry Logic"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Outpainting steps can occasionally produce artefacts — sudden colour shifts, incorrect perspective, or texture discontinuities. For production pipelines, implement per-step quality checks:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "import numpy as np\nfrom PIL import Image\n\ndef colour_continuity_score(prev_strip: np.ndarray, new_strip: np.ndarray) -> float:\n    \"\"\"\n    Measure mean absolute colour difference at the seam between\n    the last 16px of the previous region and the first 16px of the new one.\n    Lower is better; >30 suggests a visible discontinuity.\n    \"\"\"\n    left = prev_strip[:, -16:].astype(float)   # rightmost 16 cols of prior content\n    right = new_strip[:, :16].astype(float)    # leftmost 16 cols of new content\n    return float(np.abs(left - right).mean())\n\n\ndef outpaint_step_with_retry(\n    pipe, crop, mask, prompt, negative_prompt,\n    prev_canvas_np, x_start, max_retries=3, score_threshold=30.0,\n):\n    best_result = None\n    best_score = float(\"inf\")\n\n    for attempt in range(max_retries):\n        result = pipe(\n            prompt=prompt, negative_prompt=negative_prompt,\n            image=crop, mask_image=mask,\n            strength=1.0, guidance_scale=8.0, num_inference_steps=40,\n        ).images[0]\n        result_np = np.array(result)\n\n        score = colour_continuity_score(\n            prev_canvas_np[:, :x_start + 128],  # prior region\n            result_np,\n        )\n        if score < best_score:\n            best_score = score\n            best_result = result_np\n        if best_score < score_threshold:\n            break\n\n    return best_result, best_score"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "horizontalRule"
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "SDXL Outpainting at Higher Resolution"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "SDXL inpainting operates at 1024×1024, which allows more detail per window and larger step sizes. The pipeline is identical but uses "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "StableDiffusionXLInpaintPipeline",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " and a 1024-wide window:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "from diffusers import StableDiffusionXLInpaintPipeline\nimport torch\n\npipe_xl = StableDiffusionXLInpaintPipeline.from_pretrained(\n    \"diffusers/stable-diffusion-xl-1.0-inpainting-0.1\",\n    torch_dtype=torch.float16,\n    use_safetensors=True,\n).to(\"cuda\")\n\n# Same algorithm; use window=1024 and step_size=256\n# Results have ~2× the detail per generated pixel\n# GPU memory: ~12 GB VRAM required for SDXL inpainting"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "SDXL's larger UNet handles wider context windows better, making the 256px step size viable without quality loss. The tradeoff is GPU memory: SDXL inpainting needs ~12 GB VRAM versus ~6 GB for SD 1.5."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "horizontalRule"
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Key Takeaways"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "bulletList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Outpainting is inpainting with an exterior mask. The canvas is extended, the original is pasted inside, and the new border region is regenerated iteratively."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Use step_size = 25% of the window (e.g. 128px for a 512px window) and always re-paste original pixels after each step to prevent drift."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Anchored prompts that describe the visible scene (lighting, texture, environment) produce far more consistent extensions than prompts that only describe what to add."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "For architectural or perspective-heavy scenes, add a depth ControlNet to propagate spatial structure across extension steps."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "SDXL outpainting at 1024px windows produces 2× the detail per step but requires ~12 GB VRAM and works best with step_size=256."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      }
